Introduction

As part of an integrated pest management program, pesticides (especially herbicides, insecticides, nematicides, and fungicides) remain a crucial component of crop protection. Pesticides provide farmers with an efficient tool for controlling pests and, when used appropriately, prevent yield loss that could threaten food security1 and cause devastating economic losses2,3. In the United States, over 95% of corn and soybean hectares are treated with pesticides each year4.

Despite the benefits, pesticide usage in agriculture can have detrimental side effects on non-target organisms through misuse of pesticide products, off-target movement of applied pesticides, and incidental exposure within the field or other application site. As awareness of the potential for these negative effects has increased over time, public scrutiny of pesticides has also increased. Regulatory agencies and agricultural stakeholders have continuously sought to better balance the risks and benefits of pesticide usage. Most recently, the U.S. Environmental Protection Agency (EPA) has sought to increase compliance with the Endangered Species Act for its regulatory decisions5.

Corn and soybeans are among the most important agricultural crops in the United States, produced on approximately 165 million acres in 20226. Between 1960 and 1980, the volume of pesticides applied to corn and soybean increased 9- and 50-fold, respectively, in the United States4. Some of this increase is attributable to changes in crop area, since harvested acres of corn increased by 2% and harvested soybean acres increased by 187% over the same 20-year period7. By 1985, over 95% of the planted corn and soybean area were treated with pesticides4,8.

When adjusted for area, a steady increase in herbicide application intensity was observed between 1990 and 20159,10. Previous authors have suggested that increases in herbicide usage may have been driven by the widespread adoption of biotechnology-derived herbicide-resistant crops11,12. However, herbicide usage has increased more quickly in conventionally-bred crops like wheat and rice9,10, which suggests adoption of biotech varieties is not the only factor contributing to increased pesticide usage. Fungicide usage has been predicted to rise in response to climate change, increased evolution of fungicide resistance, and spread of invasive fungal species13,14. Insecticide usage has increased over this time period, but the types of active ingredients have also changed. As a result of more stringent regulation by the U.S. EPA and the passage of the Food Quality Protection Act in 1996, synthetic insecticides applied in agriculture have shifted over time from reliance on broad-spectrum organophosphate and N-methyl carbamate insecticides to more targeted neonicotinoids and less toxic pyrethroids15.

Evaluating the risk of pesticides to non-target organisms is a necessary and complex task that requires detailed information on active ingredients, application rates, exposure routes, toxicity and other effects on non-target organisms, and environmental fate of the chemical and its degredates15,16. Scientists and regulatory agencies have developed numerous methods to evaluate the environmental risks associated with pesticide usage, including pesticide risk indicators incorporating varied information, such as physico-chemical properties of active ingredients, use parameters including application rates and timings, environmental persistence and fate, and acute and chronic toxicity to different organisms10,16,17. Nonetheless, the assessment of pesticide risks is frequently based on incomplete knowledge, making the determination of the overall risk of pesticide use difficult and, often times, uncertain. Pesticide risk assessment in a regulatory context relies on large quantities of data17, complex models18, and a weight of evidence to support legally justifiable decision-making processes with sometimes enormous impacts. The objective of academic work on this topic is often more exploratory and expository16,19,20.

A first step in a retrospective analysis of potential ecological risk of pesticides is to compile existing empirical toxicity data. The ECOTOXicology Knowledgebase (ECOTOX Ver 5, www.epa.gov/ecotox) currently represents the worldâ€™s largest compilation of curated ecotoxicity data, providing data for assessments of risk and for ecological research for over 12,000 combinations of chemicals and species with over one million test results from over 50,000 references21. Managed by US EPA, it provides transparent and comprehensive information about toxicity measures and endpoints such as lethal doses and concentrations (LD50 and LC50), and other sublethal effects on both aquatic and terrestrial organisms.

Among terrestrial organisms, insect pollinators are widely used as the primary surrogate invertebrate species for environmental risk assessment. Regulatory agencies such as US EPA and the European Food Safety Agency (EFSA) require the submission of insect pollinator toxicity data when registering pesticides, in part, because these species provide critical ecosystem services22,23. Pollinators, including honey bees (Apis mellifera), are at risk for several reasons, including pesticide usage24. Honey bees also represent a useful surrogate species for ecotoxicology studies because of the availability of standardized rearing and testing protocols for lab and field experiments22, their ability to interact with pesticides through different exposure pathways25, and their sensitivity to pesticides relative to other bee species26. Honey bees represent the most well-studied indicator of insect health in US agricultural lands and have the most comprehensive ecotoxicology data set available. As such, honey bees are useful for assessing how pesticide risks to non-target invertebrates have changed over time on a relative basis15.

Because corn and soybeans represent such a large crop area with intensive pesticide usage in the United States, any improvements in pesticide usage in these crops could have an out-sized impact on the health of non-target organisms. The objective of this study was to combine honey bee toxicological endpoints with pesticide usage and yield data for corn and soybeans to (1) quantify how the average overall toxicity of agricultural pesticides to honey bees used in the United States has changed over time; and (2) determine how specific pesticides and pest targets contribute to the overall non-target pesticide hazard to insects. This information will help inform the debate on whether major domestic agricultural systems have become more or less ecologically efficient and sustainable over time, and will allow more holistic prioritization of future pest management efforts.

Methods

Data sources

Pesticide usage and crop data

Proprietary pesticide usage data were obtained in May of 2023 from the FarmTrak Chemical Use Survey conducted by Kynetec. Kynetec FarmTrak Chemical Use is a market research dataset that uses targeted surveys of agricultural producers to develop usage estimates that are statistically representative at the state level, and when combined are nationally representative. The survey data are publicly available but require a subscription fee for access. Kynetec surveys for herbicides, insecticides, fungicides, plant growth regulators, and nematicides. The FarmTrak data, like many other public and proprietary data sources, does not include seed treatments because of methodological difficulties gathering this information from growers. This is an important caveat to note, given the high proportion of planted acreage that is known to have a seed treatment.

Data used for this research included pesticide volume applied, treated acreage, timing of pesticide applications, and target pests for corn and soybean from 1998 through 2020. Application timings from the original FarmTrak dataset were aggregated into either before crop emergence (PRE) or after crop emergence (POST). National estimates of crop yield and area planted to corn and soybean for each year was obtained from the USDA National Agricultural Statistics Service7.

Honey bee toxicity data

Updated adult acute contact LD50 values for honey bee (Apis mellifera) were obtained for as many pesticide active ingredients in the FarmTrak Chemical Usage dataset as possible. Our analysis is limited to the adult acute contact toxicity due to incompleteness of most other toxicity endpoints (such as oral acute or chronic endpoints22). Adult acute contact LD50 values were obtained from the following sources: (1) the U.S. EPA ECOTOX database21, (2) Supporting Table S1 from Farruggia et al.22, (3) manually searching pesticide ecological risk assessments supporting registration and re-evaluation posted to the public docket at Regulations.gov, and (4) communications with EPA personnel from the Office of Pesticide Programsâ€™ Environmental Fate and Effects Division.

The ECOTOX database was the preferred source for all pesticide toxicity data. For each active ingredient in the FarmTrak Chemical Use dataset, adult acute contact LD50 values were downloaded from ECOTOX. For many active ingredients, ECOTOX reports multiple toxicity endpoints. Some are exact estimates (e.g.Â LD50 = 13 ug/bee). Some estimates are listed as inequalities, where the original study was unable to quantify an exact endpoint (e.g.Â LD50 > 100 ug/bee). For active ingredients with multiple adult acute contact toxicity values reported, we used the following selection criteria to select a single toxicity value for each ai:

  1. if there was only one exact estimate and one or more inequality estimates the exact estimate was selected.
  2. if there were multiple exact estimates, the lowest (most toxic) value was selected.
  3. if there were no exact estimates, the lowest (most toxic) inequality was selected.

For some active ingredients, the database included toxicity estimates from studies performed with both technical active ingredient and formulated (or typical end use) product. For our analysis we always selected the conservative (i.e., most toxic) endpoint, regardless of whether that endpoint was derived from a study with technical grade active ingredient or formulated product. After these selection criteria were applied to the ECOTOX data, these toxicity values were compared with those published by Farruggia et al.22. In nearly all cases, the ECOTOX values were the same, but for 6 pesticides, the values reported by Farruggia et al.22 were lower (i.e. more toxic) than those reported in ECOTOX. For five of those six pesticides, the Farruggia et al.22 values were used in our analysis to ensure we used the most conservative toxicity estimates available. One estimate from Farrugia et al.22 was determined to be an error; dicamba adult acute contact toxicity was listed correctly in ECOTOX and so that value was used. Finally, for any active ingredient in the FarmTrak Chemical Use dataset that did not have toxicity values in ECOTOX or Farruggia et al.22, pesticide registration and re-evaluation documents (which include the most recent ecological risk assessments, conducted approximately every 15 years for registered pesticides) were searched manually to obtain honey bee adult acute contact toxicity values.

In total, there were 205 pesticide active ingredients reported by FarmTrak Chemical Use survey respondents as being applied to either corn or soybean during the period 1998 to 2020. Of those, 57 active ingredients were reported by 2 or fewer survey respondents in any given year and had fewer than 10 reports in the entire 22-year period. It is possible that these may represent mis-reporting; to determine whether these outliers may have an outsized impact on the results, the analysis was conducted with and without these pesticides with low sample sizes. Removal had no practical impact on data interpretation, so the pesticides with low sample sizes were retained in the final analysis.

We were unable to find reliable honey bee adult acute contact toxicity estimates for 21 pesticides reported in the FarmTrak Chemical Use dataset. Of these 21 pesticides without toxicity values, 13 were applied at less than 15,000 kg over the period 1998 to 2020, and would be unlikely to have a broad impact on honey bees on a national scale. Only 2 pesticides (tebupirimphos and ethalfluralin) were applied at over 1 million kg during the study period but did not have reliable acute contact LD50 values (Supplementary Figure 1).

Ethalfluralin is a herbicide, and was not among the top 25 most applied herbicides by weight in soybeans during the period 1998 through 2020. It is therefore unlikely to have a major impact on honey bee hazard. Conversely, tebupirimphos was the 5th most used insecticide in corn during this period. As an organophosphate insecticide, tebupirimphos is expected to be highly toxic to bees; however, its only registered use in these crops is for soil-incorporated in-furrow application at corn planting with granular products, and usage on corn has decreased over time (Supplemental Figure 2). Further, tebupirimphos remains in the soil and is not known to have any systemic properties that would result in residues entering the plantâ€™s vascular system. These chemical properties and use pattern will reduce the potential of tebupirimphos to negatively impact honey bees, so while inclusion of this insecticide would improve the overall hazard estimates in this analysis, the impact of its exclusion should not have a major impact on the overall results of this analysis.

Honey bee Toxicity Index

Pesticide usage data were separated into pesticides applied before crop emergence (PRE) and pesticides applied after crop emergence (POST). For each application timing in each crop in each year, an an area-adjusted toxicity index was calculated for each active ingredient (Eq. 1). The applied volume (kg) of each active ingredient (\(P_{vol}\)) was divided by the total planted area (\(A\)) to account for year-to-year changes in hectares planted to each crop. That value was then divided by the adult acute contact LD50 of the active ingredient to obtain a toxicity index for each active ingredient (\(TI_{ai}\)) for each , and application timing in each crop for each year.

\[TI_{ai} = (\frac{P_{vol} / A}{LD_{50}})\] [Eq. 1]

The \(TI_{ai}\) values for all pesticide active ingredients were then total within each application timing, crop, and year to derive the \(TI\) (Eq. 2). \(TI\) can be interpreted as the number of honey bee acute LD50 values (in billions) of all active ingredients applied per hectare of crop grown, and is a function of both the amount of pesticide applied and the pesticide toxicity. Greater \(TI\) values suggest greater potential impact to honey bees compared with lower \(TI\) values.

\[TI = \sum_{ai=1}^{N} TI_{ai}\] [Eq. 2]

Target Pest Toxicity Index

For each pesticide application, FarmTrak Chemical Use data includes which pest species were reported by survey respondents as the target for the pesticide application. A target pest toxicity index (\(TI_{pest}\)) was calculated using this information. For each active ingredient, the volume applied targeting a particular pest (\(P_{pest}\)) was divided by the total volume of the active ingredient applied (\(P_{total}\)). This proportion was then multiplied by that active ingredientâ€™s proportion of the total toxicity index (\(TI\)). The \(TI_{pest}\) can be interpreted as the relative impact that different pest species have on the overall pesticide hazard to honey bees in corn or soybeans. A pest species with a greater \(TI_{pest}\) value is responsible for pesticide applications with greater potential impact to honey bees than a pest species with a lower \(TI_{pest}\).

\[TI_{pest} = \sum_{ai=1}^{N}(P_{pest} / P_{total}) * (TI_{ai} / TI)\] [Eq. 3]

Eco-Efficiency

Eco-efficiency (\(E\)) was calculated for each year, crop, and application timing by dividing either national crop yield (ton/ha) estimates or national production value estimates7 by the \(TI\). \(E\) can be interpreted as the crop yield or economic value of crop yield produced per honey bee LD50 applied. Higher values of \(E\) suggest greater eco-efficiency, or less non-target hazard per unit of production compared to lower values of \(E\).

\[E = \frac{Y}{TI}\]

Results and Discussion

The total honey bee \(TI\) for all active ingredients combined over all application timings during the years 1998 through 2020 was 3.3-times greater in corn compared to soybean (Figure 1). This suggests that pesticide usage in corn during this period was more hazardous to honey bees compared to those used in soybean. However, relative risk to honey bees and many other pollinator species is expected to be lower if pesticides are applied before crop emergence, as there are fewer pollinators expected to visit the field before the crop is established. In corn, only 12% of the total \(TI\) was applied after crop emergence when negative impacts are more likely, whereas 94% of the total \(TI\) applied to soybean was applied after crop emergence. If only pesticides applied after crop emergence were considered, then the total \(TI\) for soybeans was 2.5-times greater compared to corn. Qualitatively, itâ€™s also worth noting that bees are less likely to actively forage on corn since it is only a significant source of pollen, whereas soybeans flowers provide both nectar and pollen resources27.

Figure 1. total honey bee toxicity index applied to corn or soybean during the period 1998 through 2020 by pesticide type and application timing.

For both crops, a vast majority of \(TI\) was driven by insecticide usage, as expected, because insecticides are inherently more acutely toxic to insects, by design, compared to most herbicides and fungicides. In corn, insecticides were responsible for nearly 98% of \(TI\). In soybean, insecticides were responsible for 93% of the total \(TI\). In terms of total volume applied, herbicides are more heavily used in both corn and soybean; however, because \(TI\) accounts both for applied volume and inherent acute toxicity, the relative toxicity of insecticides to honey bees outweighs the greater herbicide usage in this metric. Because insecticides are the primary driver of overall acute risk to honey bees (and likely other pollinators), we will only discuss insecticides further in this manuscript. We will suggest, however, that future research aimed at chronic endpoints could provide nuanced insights into overall risk contributions from other groups of chemicals (like herbicides and fungicides).

Over time, the insecticide \(TI\) in corn has shifted from primarily PRE applications to nearly equal contributions from PRE and POST applications (Figure 2). During the period 2000 to 2005, 94% of the honey bee \(TI\) from corn insecticides resulted from applications made before crop emergence. More recently, from 2015 to 2020, approximately 51% of honey bee \(TI\) resulted from applications made before corn emergence. In corn, the toxicity index resulting from POST applications has increased approximately 4.1-fold, from 0.054 to 0.22.

Figure 2. Honey bee adult acute contact toxicity index for insecticides applied to corn or soybean before (PRE) or after (POST) crop emergence. Insecticide surveys for soybean began in 2004.

In soybeans, insecticides were not not present in the FarmTrak Chemical Use dataset before 2004. During the period 2005 to 2010, 99% of the insecticide \(TI\) resulted from applications after crop emergence, although the total insecticide \(TI\) was still comparatively low. More recently, between 2015 to 2020, 97% of soybean insecticide \(TI\) resulted from POST applications, and exceeded the insecticide \(TI\) associated with POST corn insecticide usage.

Two pesticides, fipronil and chlorpyrifos, were responsible for a majority of the total insecticide \(TI\) from PRE applications to corn until approximately 2010 (Figure 3A), when all uses of fipronil on corn were cancelled in the United States28. After 2010, bifenthrin became the largest contributor to \(TI\) in both PRE (Figure 3B) and POST (Figure 3C) application timings in corn. Insecticide \(TI\) resulting from PRE applications to soybeans remained low throughout the study period (Figure 2). Insecticide applications were relatively uncommon in soybean before 2006, with annual average volume of less than 1 million kg applied dating back to 199429. Three insecticides (bifenthrin, chlorpyrifos, and lambda-cyhalothrin) accounted for a majority of the insecticide \(TI\) resulting from POST applications to soybean since 2006 (Figure 3D).

Figure 3. Contribution of insecticide active ingredients to honey bee adult acute contact toxicity index applied PRE to corn (A, B), POST to corn (C), or POST to soybean (D). Panel B shows the period from 2012 to 2020 for corn PRE on a zoomed-in y-axis scale. The â€˜All Other Insecticidesâ€™ category includes 2% of the total corn toxicity index applied PRE, 10% of the total corn toxicity index applied POST, and 13% of the total soybean toxicity index. Insecticide surveys for soybean began in 2004.

Pesticide Target Toxicity Index

In corn, insect pests from the orders Coleoptera and Lepidoptera contributed most to the overall insecticide \(TI\) (Figure 4), followed by Hemipteran insects and spider mites (Trombidiformes). In corn, there was a decreasing trend for Coleoptera (P < 0.001) and Lepidoptera (P < 0.001) contributions to the \(TI_{pest}\) over time. Hemiptera pests contribution to the insecticide \(TI\) increased over time (P = 0.001). There was also an increase in the contribution of the â€˜Unknownâ€™ pest target category (P < 0.001), which included survey responses that did not answer the question of which pest species was being targeted. Temporal trends for other taxa were not statistically significant in corn (Figure 4).

For PRE applications in corn since 2015, corn rootworm beetles, wireworms, and grubs were the largest contributors to the insecticide \(TI\) among Coleoptera pests, while cutworms of various species were the greatest contributors among Lepidopteran pests (Supplementary Table). Diptera had a relatively low contribution to the insecticide \(TI\) applied PRE, which is somewhat surprising since seedcorn maggot is considered a major pest in some corn growing regions. The insecticide \(TI\) resulting from POST applications in corn (Figure 4) was driven heavily by corn rootworm beetles (Coleoptera), Japanese beetles (Coleoptera), and stink bugs (Hemiptera), presumably due to potential for silk feeding. Aphids (Hemiptera) and cutworm species (Lepidoptera) were also important drivers of the corn insecticide \(TI\) from POST applications since 2015.

Figure 4. Contribution of insect pests to the honey bee adult acute contact toxicity index; corn pesticides applied after crop emergence, 1998-2020.

In soybean, Hemiptera pests were the greatest contributor to the insecticide \(TI\), although there was a significant decrease in its contribution over time (P < 0.001). Stink bugs and aphid species were the greatest contributors to the insecticide \(TI\) among hemipteran pest species (Supplementary Table). Lepidopteran pest contribution to \(TI\) increased over time (P = 0.005). Since 2015, the Lepidoptera pests contributing most to the insecticide \(TI\) were various species referred to as â€˜wormsâ€™ by survey respondents (including corn earworm and boll worm), â€˜loopersâ€™ (cabbage and soybean), and armyworms. Leaf beetles and Japanese beetles were the most impactful Coleoptera pest species in terms of contribution to the insecticide \(TI\) from POST applications to soybean since 2015. Similar to corn, the â€˜Unknownâ€™ category also increased (P < 0.001) due to survey respondents not answering the question about the targeted pest(s).

Figure 5. Contribution of insect pests to the honey bee adult acute contact toxicity index; soybean pesticides applied after crop emergence, 1998-2020.

Insecticide Eco-Efficiency

Corn and soybean yields have steadily increased in the United States between 1998 and 2020 (Figure 6A, 6D). Insecticide eco-efficiency for both corn yield (Figure 6B) and corn production value (Figure 6C) increased substantially between 1998 through 2011, due to the observed yield increase and concurrent reduction in insecticide \(TI\). However, even though corn yield continued to increase after 2011, a substantially lower corn insecticide eco-efficiency was observed beginning in 2012. Corn insecticide eco-efficiency decreased from 2012 through 2020, largely due to increased \(TI\) from bifenthrin usage. In spite of increasing soybean yields from 1998 through 2020, insecticide eco-efficiency declined slowly in soybean throughout the period 2005 through 2020 (Figures 6C; 6D) due to increasing \(TI\).

The units associated with eco-efficiency (crop yield or value per unit of \(TI\)) are difficult to interpret in a practical way, but the trend over time provides insight into whether the observed increases in crop yield are out-pacing changes in hazard to honey bees from insecticides. Because both corn and soybean yield continued to increase throughout this period, the flat to declining trend in insecticide eco-efficiency in recent years suggests that the relative increase observed in the honey bee \(TI\) is out-pacing the relative increases in corn yields since 2012, at least on the national scale.

Figure 6. Corn (A) and soybean (B) yield, and honey bee eco-efficiency index for insecticides applied to corn or soybean after crop emergence. Yield eco-efficiency numerator is crop yield in ton/ha (B, D); value eco-efficiency numerator is the farm value of crop production in $/ha (E, F); denominator for all eco-efficiency values is the insecticide \(TI\) from POST applications.

The eco-efficiency results reported here suggest that the honey bee hazard from recent insecticide usage in corn and soybean is increasing more rapidly than the yield gains observed over the same period. There has also been a shift for an increased honey bee insecticide hazard being applied after crop emergence when there is likely to be greater exposure potential to honey bees and other pollinators. In corn, the increased insecticide hazard applied after crop emergence has, perhaps, been somewhat offset by a relatively larger decrease in insecticide hazard applied before crop emergence. However, since pollinator presence in corn fields is undoubtedly greater after crop emergence, this trade-off is difficult to quantify. From a practical standpoint, if foraging is less in corn relative to other crops, that could reduce the real-world impact of the observed increase in hazard.

In soybeans, insecticide usage increased quickly after 2004 when the FarmTrak Chemical Use survey first reported insecticide usage. In more recent years (2015 to 2020), POST insecticide use in soybeans has resulted in a greater insecticide hazard to honey bees compared to corn. This uptick is not surprising, given the discovery of the invasive soybean aphid in 2000, and more recently, the emerging importance of plant bugs and stink bugs in soybeans, particularly in the Southern United States. However, this trend is especially concerning because soybeans are more attractive to pollinating bees for the collection of nectar than corn27. While corn pollen can be consumed by honey bees, overall visitation per hectare is likely to be much higher in soybeans when the crops are flowering.

In corn, the increased insecticide hazard applied after crop emergence has been offset by a substantial decrease in insecticide hazard applied before crop emergence, and therefore, the total hazard may be negligible. But in soybean, insecticide usage went from nearly non-existent before 2004 to greater insecticide hazard to honey bees than corn in the period 2015 to 2020. Soybeans are more attractive to pollinating bees for the collection of nectar than corn27. While corn pollen can be consumed, overall visitation per hectare is likely to be much higher in soybeans when the crops are flowering.

This analysis, like most others published before, does not include pesticides applied as seed treatments. Public data (such as USDA surveys and census data) as well as proprietary sources like the FarmTrak Chemical Use survey data do not include seed treatments. The impact of this data limitation is an underestimate of the hazard resulting from applications made PRE crop emergence; however, because honey bee exposure to pesticides applied as seed treatments is generally lower than those applied after crop emergence, the magnitude of this underestimate is difficult to ascertain. It is most commonly understood that with the exception of potential systemic insecticide movement in the crop plant, the greatest potential exposure from seed treatment use is at planting, when residues can â€˜dust-offâ€™ and drift to adjacent habitat that is attractive to bees. Industry has been making efforts to minimize dust-off potential with new planter and seed lubricant technology. But regardless, we emphasize that this exposure pathway is not part of our analysis.

It is also important to appropriately characterize exposure as a fundamental component to real-world risk. The \(TI\) in our analysis focuses on hazard, and does not quantitatively include exposure. This is important, because while insecticide \(TI\) values from PRE applications to corn are relatively high before 2010, the actual likelihood of bee exposure is negligible from many of those insecticide applications, particularly for active ingredients that are not systemic. Future research could evaluate impacts on non-target soil taxa and diversity, but flying insects that are present or foraging after crop emergence, the actual risk posed from even high \(TI\) active ingredients applied at before crop emergence could be widely negligible.

Broadly, it is important to understand why honey bee hazard from POST insecticide usage has been increasing in recent years. Is this increase due to a perceived increase in pest pressure, or a perceived increase in the economic damage caused by insect pests? Or perhaps the cost of certain pesticides has decreased, consequently caused increase use as a preemptive yield protection practice. While speculative, it is possible that the increased prevalence of â€˜no answerâ€™ in response to the target pest may be evidence for this possibility. Anecdotally, we are aware of cases where insecticides may be added to a planned fungicide or herbicide application because the grower is already spending significant costs to treat the field anyway. Such an approach may be rational in terms of a grower achieving cheap insurance against a pest outbreak, such applications may run counter to the fundamental principles of IPM. Unless justified by other factors such as site history, local pest biology, or other evidence for high likelihood of an outbreak, IPM typically dictates that application decisions should be driven by economic thresholds rather than precautionary or preventative treatments. We suggest that more research is needed to explore whether preventative insecticide applications are becoming more common, and what sorts of decision inputs are driving pest management decisions. The underlying cause of increased non-target hazards must be understood to develop research programs or devise policy actions that have a positive impact8.

To our knowledge, this analysis is the first to estimate the relative contribution of different pest species to non-target impacts of pesticide usage. The information gleaned from this approach provides multiple avenues for future research that could benefit non-target insect species like honey bees. For example, bifenthrin appears to be the active ingredient that has contributed most to recent increases in insecticide hazard to honey bees in both corn and soybean. At least for the usage where a target pest is reported, the pests that appear to drive bifenthrin usage include spider mites, corn rootworm, and Western bean cutworm in corn; and stink bugs and soybean aphids in soybean. We note that one limitation of the target pest data in the FarmTrak Chemical Use dataset is that tank-mix artifacts can arise. For example, if a grower is applying an insecticide and a miticide concurrently, FarmTrak data may associate mites with the insecticide if data for that specific active ingredient are pulled by target pest, even though itâ€™s actually the miticide targeting mites. We suspect that some of the mite usage associated with pyrethroids (known in many cases to flare mites rather than control them) may be spurious for applications where miticides were tank-mixed. In any case, finding cost-effective efficacious pesticides with reduced non-target toxicity, or developing non-chemical approaches to manage these pests is ultimately crucial to reduce the overall non-target hazard from insecticide uses.

Coleoptera and Lepidoptera (rootworm species, silk-eating insects, and cutworms) were the greatest contributors to the corn insecticide \(TI\), and therefore research efforts targeting these species are likely to have the greatest impact on lowering the non-target hazard to honey bees in corn production. Conversely, Hemipteran pests (stink bugs and aphid species) are the pest targets causing the greatest insecticide hazard to honey bees in soybean. Insecticides targeting these few pests represent an out-sized proportion of the relative insecticide hazard to honey bees in the US. This is not surprising given the increasing prevalence of stink bugs in the Southern United States and the nearly ubiquitous presence of soybean aphids since introduction to the U.S. was first discovered in 200130. Efforts to reduce the need for pesticides to control these species, or education efforts on whether treatments are actually needed, would likely pay dividends in reducing non-target risks to insects like honey bees.
